17
00:01:05,891 --> 00:01:08,195
"'Cough, be damned!

18
00:01:08,475 --> 00:01:10,318
Pass along that return-bucket!'

19
00:01:11,328 --> 00:01:12,290
There again!

20
00:01:12,350 --> 00:01:13,392
There it is!

21
00:01:13,412 --> 00:01:16,419
It sounds like two or three sleepers turning over.

22
00:01:16,459 --> 00:01:17,100
Now!

23
00:01:17,922 --> 00:01:20,067
Karamba have done, shipmate, will ye?

24
00:01:20,227 --> 00:01:25,017
It's the three soaked biscuits ye eat for supper turning over inside of ye nothing else.

25
00:01:25,599 --> 00:01:26,440
Look to the bucket.

26
00:01:27,583 --> 00:01:30,028
Say what ye will, shipmate.

27
00:01:30,008 --> 00:01:31,430
Ay, then ye's.

28
00:01:32,091 --> 00:01:39,782
Ay, you are the chap, ain't ye, that heard the hum of the old Quakeress's knitting needles fifty miles at sea from Nantucket.

29
00:01:40,162 --> 00:01:41,024
You're the chap.

30
00:01:42,065 --> 00:01:42,966
Grin away, well.

31
00:01:43,427 --> 00:01:44,689
We'll see what turns up.

32
00:01:44,769 --> 00:01:54,883
Hark ye, Capico, there is somebody down in the afterhold that has not yet been seen on deck, and I suspect our old mogul knows something of it too.

33
